    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="1499"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1499">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.51/375.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 26, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In reference to your allusion to a canal project in your February 14, the bankers
                    have expressed their wish to know if there is any objection to inclusion of that
                    project in their new proposals to Nicaragua. Department replied February 24 that
                    there was none, provided that the loan contract contain the specification that
                    there shall be no alienation to any foreign company or government except with
                    the consent of this Government, and provided further that no trans-isthmian
                    route shall be established without the advice and consent of this
                    Government.</p>
                <p>The bankers advise the Department that their representatives will be directed to
                    drop the matter for the present if either the concession itself or the insertion
                    of the foregoing provisos in the loan contract would endanger the latter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
